\n- Old `crdb-certs` ca.crt: likely the toolbox CA (`1F:BB:1C:...`)\n- Toolbox CA: `1F:BB:1C:...` valid until 2036\n\nIf the original cert was signed by the toolbox CA, then both node 0 and node 2 should have that CA in memory and be able to verify the old node cert. But node 2 is still failing verification somehow—I need to figure out why the toolbox CA isn't validating the 2031 cert.\n\nActually, wait—I already patched the `crdb-certs` secret, so I can't check what the original CA was. But maybe I can find it in CockroachDB's etcd state or check what CA is actually loaded in node 0's process memory right now to understand the mismatch.\n\nLooking at the error more carefully: node 2 is the client trying to connect to node 0, and it's saying it can't verify node 0's certificate because it was signed by an unknown authority. This means node 2 has the toolbox CA loaded, but node 0's cert was signed by a different CA. Looking at the old `crdb-old-cert` configmap, I see it tracks a different cert (expiring Jul 3) with fingerprint `84:D0:30:...`, but this doesn't tell me what CA signed the original node cert from 2031. Let me try checking the CockroachDB admin API endpoints to see what cert fingerprint the running process actually reports.\n\nActually, I'll use openssl s_client to connect to node 0 from node 2 and see what certificate it's presenting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":823,"cache_read_input_tokens":64574,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":823},"output_tokens":45,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a6ecc798-a3bf-4f9b-a2fb-eec9c2e97d5e","uuid":"ea37f950-1556-4431-8c80-d86d611df74e","request_id":"req_011Ccc4jVNBHXvRoSfkin25z"}
